ex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe twelve essays in this volume propose new directions in the analysis of class. John R. Hall argues that recent historical and intellectual developments require reworking basic assumptions about classes and their dynamics. The contributors effectively abandon the notion of a transcendent class struggle. They seek instead to understand the historically contingent ways in which economic interests are pursued under institutionally, socially, and culturally structured circumstances.In his introduction, Hall proposes a neo-Weberian venue intended to bring the most promising contemporary approaches to class analysis into productive exchange with one another. Some of the chapters that follow rework how classes are conceptualized. Others offer historical and sociological reflections on questions of class identity. A third cluster focuses on the politics of class mobilizations and social movements in contexts of national and global economic change.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aSocial classes. 4aPhilosophy. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Social Classes & Economic Disparity.2bisacsh1 aBiernacki, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrustein, William, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDonnelly, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHall, John R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHall, John R., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJoyce, Patrick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLamont, Michele, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRose, Sonya O.,